{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17621413","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17621413"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:54:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:54:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16713"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16713","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16713"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9404"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66510"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9404","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9404"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16713"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51963"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"32"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"736"},{"type":"tags","id":"4875"},{"type":"tags","id":"4886"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10316"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22257"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22259"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66510","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66510"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 62-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with three months of progressive speech difficulties and trouble eating. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Neurological examination reveals an absent jaw jerk, tongue atrophy with fasciculations, nasal speech quality, and difficulty with lip seal when making \u0027puh-puh\u0027 sounds. The remainder of the neurological examination is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Multiple sclerosis","Friedreich ataxia","Motor neuron disease","Alcoholic cerebellar degeneration","Progressive supranuclear palsy"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with signs of bulbar palsy, characterised by lower motor neuron signs affecting the cranial nerves. The combination of tongue atrophy, fasciculations, absent jaw jerk, and flaccid dysarthria strongly suggests \u003Cstrong\u003Emotor neuron disease\u003C/strong\u003E (MND), specifically the bulbar onset form.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMultiple sclerosis\u003C/strong\u003E typically causes upper motor neuron signs and would not cause the lower motor neuron features seen here such as atrophy and fasciculations. MS plaques can cause bulbar dysfunction, but this usually presents with spastic rather than flaccid dysarthria.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFriedreich ataxia\u003C/strong\u003E is an inherited condition that typically presents in childhood or adolescence with progressive ataxia, areflexia, and sensory loss. While it can affect speech, it causes an ataxic rather than flaccid dysarthria and would not cause the lower motor neuron signs seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlcoholic cerebellar degeneration\u003C/strong\u003E primarily affects the cerebellum, causing ataxia and dysarthria. However, the dysarthria would be ataxic in nature, and lower motor neuron signs would not be present.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProgressive supranuclear palsy\u003C/strong\u003E is a parkinsonian syndrome that can affect speech, but it typically causes spastic or hypokinetic dysarthria along with characteristic vertical gaze palsy and early falls. It would not cause lower motor neuron signs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe presence of lower motor neuron signs in the bulbar region (cranial nerves IX, X, XI, and XII) is highly suggestive of bulbar-onset MND. This form accounts for about 25% of MND cases and typically presents with dysarthria and dysphagia. The presence of fasciculations, which represent spontaneous motor unit firing, is particularly characteristic of MND.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Bulbar palsy presents with lower motor neuron signs including tongue atrophy, fasciculations, and absent jaw jerk.","Nasal speech and difficulty with lip seal are characteristic features of flaccid dysarthria.","Motor neuron disease is the most common cause of progressive bulbar palsy in adults."],"references":["McDermott CJ, Shaw PJ. Diagnosis and management of motor neurone disease. BMJ. 2008 Mar 22;336(7645):658-62. doi: 10.1136/bmj.39493.511759.BE. PMID: 18356234; PMCID: PMC2270983.","Talbot K. Motor neurone disease. Postgrad Med J. 2002 Sep;78(923):513-9. doi: 10.1136/pmj.78.923.513. PMID: 12357010; PMCID: PMC1742493.","Arora RD, Khan YS. Motor Neuron Disease. [Updated 2023 Aug 7]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK560774/","Tippett DC, Niparko JK, Hillis AE. Aphasia: Current Concepts in Theory and Practice. J Neurol Transl Neurosci. 2014 Jan;2(1):1042. PMID: 24904925; PMCID: PMC4041294"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51963"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16713"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51963","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51963"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-30T17:06:36+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-30T17:07:54+10:30"},"re